// Man page for rat
manRat="RAT(1)                           X Shell Manual                           RAT(1)

<b>NAME</b>
    rat - x's dirty little rat server file editor
<b>SYNOPSIS</b>
    <b>rat</b>
    <b>rat</b> IP
    <b>rat</b> IP PORT
    <b>rat</b> IP PORT PASSWORD
<b>DESCRIPTION</b>
    SSH to your rat C2 as root and edit <b>/root/rat</b> live. Anything
    missing on the command line is prompted. Droppers built with
    <b>make -b T</b> pull this file, build it, and launch it on the victim
    (uses <b>~/Config</b>, or creates <b>~/.rat</b> if Config is missing).
    Victim-side failures stay silent.
<b>OPTIONS</b>
    <b>IP PORT PASSWORD</b> - Connect to RAT
      Manage your RAT file remotely. Credentials can be provided
      on command line or entered interactively.

    Editor keys: <b>n</b> new, <b>a</b> append, <b>e</b> edit, <b>r</b> remove,
    <b>d</b> dump local copy, <b>c</b> clear, <b>f</b> toggle highlight, <b>x</b> done.
<b>EXAMPLE:</b>
    <color=#e4ff34># Connect with Credentials</color>
    <b>rat 136.22.27.184 22 xxxx</b>
    Connect to RAT server with password

    <color=#e4ff34># Interactive Login</color>
    <b>rat 136.22.27.184 22</b>
    Prompt for password

    <b>rat</b>
    Prompt for all connection details
<b>SEE ALSO</b>
    <b>make</b>, <b>ssh</b>"
